<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1881-06-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1881-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="166" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d166">
                    <head>No. 166.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Blaine</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Angell</persName></hi>.</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1881-06-29"><hi rend="italic">June</hi> 29,
                            1881</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 109.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 152 of April 30 last, has
                        been received. It narrates the particulars of a disturbance by the Chinese
                        at the American Presbyterian Mission, at Peking, and describes the measures
                        taken by the Chinese authorities, at your earnest solicitation, to suppress
                        it.</p>
                    <p>In reply I desire to extend my congratulations to you, and to express my
                        gratification at the successful result of the measures adopted to quell the
                        disturbance.</p>
                    <p>I am, sir, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>JAMES G. BLAINE.</signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>